    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-02-19T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-02-19T21:00:00-05:00" n="713"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d713">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 652.119/566a</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_WJE1"
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Willard</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-02-19T21:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 19, 1918, 9 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>896. Referring your Nos. 1058 and 1073.<note n="1" xml:id="d713fn1">No. 1073 not
                        printed.</note> There are no Spanish steamers held. <hi rend="italic"
                        >Adolfo, Jacinto Verdaguer, Miguel Jover, Andalucia, Cataluña</hi> are
                    awaiting licenses for portions of cargo such as cotton. Export licenses will be
                    granted immediately upon Spain’s signing the agreements with the French and
                    United States, their cargoes to count as a part of the monthly quotas provided
                    for in article 4. This would permit all Spanish vessels to proceed immediately
                    upon signing agreements. You may give assurances to the above effect in whatever
                    manner is necessary to help prompt closing of agreement. During two months from
                    date of signing of the agreement no detention of vessels will be enforced whose
                    cargoes do not involve a violation of the terms of the agreement or unless
                    vessels have violated any of the regulations imposed by United States
                    authorities on all neutral tonnage clearing from American ports. You may rest
                    assured there is no discrimination against Spanish tonnage pending definite
                    agreement to be arrived at as provided in article 13.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
